Observation:
After testing two different hyperparameter configurations, the results showed a clear impact on the performance of both neural network models. In the initial setup, using a learning rate of 0.001 and 300 iterations, the Simple Neural Network achieved an accuracy of 0.7933 and an AUC of 0.8540, while the Deep Neural Network reached an accuracy of 0.7765 and an AUC of 0.8300. After modifying the parameters to a learning rate of 0.1 and 50 iterations, the Simple Neural Network showed a slight decrease in performance, with accuracy dropping to 0.7765 and AUC to 0.8464. In contrast, the Deep Neural Network improved significantly, achieving an accuracy of 0.8101 and an AUC of 0.8628. This suggests that the deeper model benefited from the higher learning rate, allowing it to converge faster and reach a better solution in fewer iterations. The results highlight how sensitive neural networks are to hyperparameter tuning and show that the Deep Neural Network performed best under the second configuration.
